There are several was to get Mock objects into your production code:

1. Parameters 

As Mr Freeman shows, you use parameters to pass the Mock into the 
class that calls it.

2 Reflection

If B is referenced in a field of A, you can use reflection to modify 
A and replace B with it&#39;s Mock.

3 Mole Pattern

Subclass A, and use the subclass to setup the Mock.  [I call this 
design the &quot;Mole Pattern&quot;]

4 Strategy Pattern

Use a Strategy design pattern.

5 Dynamic Proxy

If the B is an implementation of an Interface, you can use a Dynamic 
Proxy (new feature of Java 1.3b).  The Mock would be an 
InvocationHandler, instead of a twin of B.

6 Classloader

Use a classloader to load the Mock instead of the real class.

---

There may be other options, but these are the ones I&#39;ve heard of.  
Personally, I&#39;ve used everything except #6.  Options #1 (parameters) 
and #2 (reflection) are my favorites.  They are usually the easiest 
to implement and understand.  For #2, I&#39;ve used the 
PrivilegedAccessor.java [posted by Mr DiIorio] to make the reflection 
work simple.

I&#39;ve never seen anyone use #6 (classloaders), I think it would be fun 
to try.

- Greg


--- In junit@y..., &quot;Steve Freeman&quot; &lt;steve@m...&gt; wrote:
&gt; RE: Method Chains, was Re: Testing private methodsAlternatively, 
&gt; change from:
&gt; 
&gt; public class A {
&gt;   public void f() {
&gt;     b = new B();
&gt;     b.doSomething();
&gt;   }
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; to:
&gt; 
&gt; public class A {
&gt;   public void f(B b) {
&gt;     b.doSomething(aValue());
&gt;   }
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; The test then becomes:
&gt; 
&gt; public class TestA {
&gt;   public void testF() {
&gt;     A anA = new A(aValue);
&gt;     MockB mockB = new MockB();
&gt;     mockB.setExpectedSomething(aValue);
&gt; 
&gt;     a.f(mockB);
&gt; 
&gt;     mockB.verify();
&gt;   }
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; We have found that changing to a style where you pass behaviours 
around, rather than data, avoids things like subclassing production 
code in a test and pushes the code to flexing in the &#39;right&#39; kinda 
ways. If you can figure out what to pass in and what to verify, then 
the rest of the test usually falls out.
&gt; 
&gt; Steve
